font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:black'>Diagnosis of the disease</span></b></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:14.0pt;margin-right:0in;margin-bottom:
14.0pt;margin-left:0in;line-height:normal'><b><span style='font-size:13.5pt;
font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:black'>Questioning and inspection</span></b></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:14.0pt;margin-right:0in;margin-bottom:
14.0pt;margin-left:0in;line-height:normal'><span style='font-size:13.5pt;
font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:black'>A thorough survey of the
patient about the condition that has arisen, the presence of a previous bladder
catheterization, perineal trauma, sexually transmitted infections, previous
radiation therapy for cancer of the pelvic organs, and the patient's sexual history
is carried out.&nbsp;The diagnosis of urethral stricture necessarily includes
an examination of the penis, external opening of the urethra, perineum,
assessment of the presence or absence of changes in the foreskin, scars and
fistulas.&nbsp;In addition, an examination of the oral cavity and assessment of
the mobility of the hip and knee joints is performed.&nbsp;Then the doctor
conducts palpation (probing) of the urethra and scrotal organs, as well as a
digital examination of the rectum.</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:14.0pt;margin-right:0in;margin-bottom:
14.0pt;margin-left:0in;line-height:normal'><b><span style='font-size:13.5pt;
