<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:14.0pt;margin-right:0in;margin-bottom:
14.0pt;margin-left:0in;line-height:normal'><span style='font-size:13.5pt;
font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:black'>Depending on the severity of
the urethral stricture and the degree of deterioration, different methods of
surgical treatment are used:</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:14.0pt;margin-left:64.9pt;text-indent:
-.25in;line-height:normal'><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Symbol;
color:black'>·<span style='font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><span style='font-size:13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;
color:black'>minimally invasive surgery -&nbsp;<b>internal urethrotomy&nbsp;</b>-
dissection of the ureter wall with an instrument inserted through the
urethra.&nbsp;&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-left:64.9pt;text-indent:-.25in;line-height:
normal'><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Symbol;color:black'>·<span
style='font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><span style='font-size:13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;
color:black'>radical method -&nbsp;<b>reconstructive open surgery&nbsp;</b>-
removal of the problem area of &#8203;&#8203;the urethra, anatomical plastic or
replacement plastic, depending on the length of the affected area.&nbsp;&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-bottom:14.0pt;margin-left:64.9pt;text-indent:
-.25in;line-height:normal'><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Symbol;
color:black'>·<span style='font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><span style='font-size:13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;
color:black'>If it is impossible to carry out the operation, a&nbsp;<b>cystostomy&nbsp;</b>is&nbsp;installed&nbsp;-
a special device that is placed in the bladder in order to restore the outflow
of urine.&nbsp;&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:14.0pt;margin-right:0in;margin-bottom:
14.0pt;margin-left:0in;line-height:normal'><b><span style='font-size:13.5pt;
font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:black'>Recovery and improvement of
the quality of life</span></b></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:14.0pt;margin-right:0in;margin-bottom:
14.0pt;margin-left:0in;line-height:normal'><span style='font-size:13.5pt;
font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:black'>The recovery period after
surgery will vary depending on the surgery performed, the length of the
catheterization, and your overall health.&nbsp;The urethral catheter remains in
the urethra after all operations to treat urethral stricture.&nbsp;The minimum
period of standing of the catheter is 7 days.&nbsp;After surgery, follow-up is
necessary to ensure adequate healing of the surgical site, the absence of
possible complications such as infection, fistula formation (opening between
the urethra and the skin), recurrent stricture, urethral diverticulum
(protrusion of the urethral wall).&nbsp;Erectile dysfunction can occur
temporarily after urethral repair with resolution in almost all operated
patients six months after surgery.&nbsp;After the operation, it is necessary to
carry out control examinations, such as uroflowmetry, ultrasound of the bladder
with the study of residual urine.</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:14.0pt;margin-right:0in;margin-bottom:
14.0pt;margin-left:0in;line-height:normal'><b><span style='font-size:18.0pt;
font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:black'>Possible complications</span></b></p>

